column168: Description Of Events

XPO Logistics terminal XFO experienced a UN3082 Caromax 28 release from a 275-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-gallons of product released to a 3’ x 2’ area of the wooden trailer floor and a 1’ x 1’ area of the concrete dock floor due to a crack in the top corner of the tote. The material was transferred from the damaged tote into a new one. Absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted areas. The damaged tote was then cut up and containerized along with all impacted absorbents into (2) 55- gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: RESPONDER RESPONDED TO LEAKING PACKAGE IN PPE AND DECISION TREE. RESPONDER FOLLOWED THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET, PUT THE PACKAGE IN A SPILL TUB FOR PROCESSING.

On February 1, 2024, one (1) 330-gallon tote of UN3082 was punctured by a forklift and released approximately thirty (30) gallons of product to the dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted site.  FCE personnel deployed granular absorbents to the UN3082-impacted dock floor and swept them in with hand tools. Crews observed that they would not be able to lift the tote for a gravity feed and instead did a bucket transfer of all the remaining contents into an additional 330-gallon tote. All spent absorbents, clean up debris, and cut up 330-gallon tote were collected and containerized into five (5) 55-gallon drums for terminal disposal.

column168: On February 2, 2024, three (3) 5-gallon pails of UN1263 were punctured by a metal rod in transit and released approximately five (5) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted site. FCE personnel found three (3) damaged 5-gallon pails, removed them from the load, and placed them into one (1) 55-gallon drum that was fitted with proper labels for return to the terminal. Crews utilized granular absorbents to collect the released product from the trailer and freight, and all spent absorbents and any cleanup debris were collected and containerized into one (1) 5-gallon bucket that was taken back to the terminal by FCE personnel.
